{"title_page": "Lanc\u00f4me", "text_new": "{{about|the French perfumes and cosmetics house|the French commune|Lanc\u00f4me, Loir-et-Cher}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2016}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name\t        = Lanc\u00f4me\n| logo\t        = Lanc\u00f4me logo.svg\n| type\t        = [[Subsidiary]]\n| foundation\t= {{start date and age|1935|df=yes}}\n| founders      = Guillaume d'Ornano<br>Armand Petitjean\n| location_city = Paris\n| location_country = France\n| key_people\t= \n| industry\t= Fashion\n| parent\t= [[L'Or\u00e9al]] (1964\u2013present)\n| products\t= Perfumes and cosmetics\n| revenue\t= \n| net income    = \n| num_employees\t= \n| homepage \t= {{URL|www.lancome.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Lanc\u00f4me''' ({{IPA-fr|l\u0251\u0303kom}}) is a French luxury perfumes and cosmetics house that distributes products internationally.<ref>{{cite news|last=Chesters|first=Anna|title=A brief history of Lanc\u00f4me|url=https://www.theguardian.com/fashion/fashion-blog/2012/mar/19/brief-history-lancome|accessdate=11 March 2013|newspaper=The Guardian|date=19 March 2012}}</ref> Lanc\u00f4me is part of the [[L'Or\u00e9al]] Luxury Products division, which is its parent company and offers luxury [[skin care]], [[fragrances]], and makeup at higher-end prices.\n\n==History==\n[[Image:Lancome NYC Boutique Exterior.jpg|thumb|right|Lanc\u00f4me Boutique on NYC's Upper West Side|Lanc\u00f4me Boutique on NYC's Upper West Side]]\n\nFounded in 1935 by Guillaume d'Ornano and his business partner Armand Petitjean in France, as originally a fragrance house. The name \"Lanc\u00f4me\" was inspired by the forest of Lancosme that lies in the Indre valley in the heart of France in the region of La Brenne - the name was chosen by Guillaume's wife Elisabeth d'Ornano. The roses in the area inspired the company's symbol of the single golden rose.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vogue.in/content/exclusive-80-years-lancome-film/|title=Exclusive: 80 years of Lanc\u00f4me in a 2-minute film}}</ref>\n\nLanc\u00f4me launched its first five fragrances in 1935 at the [[Brussels International Exposition (1935)|World's Fair]] in Brussels: ''Tendre Nuit'', ''Bocages'', ''Conquete'', ''Kypre'' and ''Tropiques''. Petitjean entered into the luxury skincare market, launching Nutrix, his first \"all-purpose repair cream\" in 1936, followed by make-up, cosmetics, and skincare products. Lanc\u00f4me was acquired by L'oreal in 1964, and quickly became part of its luxury products division.\n\n==Products==\n[[File:DFS Galleria Customhouse Lanc\u00f4me 2013.jpg|thumb|Lanc\u00f4me counter at [[DFS Galleria]] Customhouse in [[Auckland]], [[New Zealand]]]]\nThe company provides fragrances, skin care, and makeup. Their most famous products include their mascaras, namely \"Hypn\u00f4se\", their Visionnaire Range which contains a patented ingredient, \"LR 2412\", aimed to improve skin texture color qualities, especially in pore reduction, fine lines and uneven skin tone.\n\nLanc\u00f4me fragrances are made in association with perfumers: Alain Astori, Annick Menardo, Daniela Roche-Andrier, Christian Biecher, [[Jacques Cavallier]], [[Calice Becker]], Pauline Zanoni, [[Maurice Roucel]], [[Thierry Wasser]], [[Christine Nagel]], Armand Petitjean, Gerard Goupy, [[Olivier Cresp]], Harry Fremont, Alberto Morillas, Dominique Ropion, Olivier Polge, [[Francis Kurkdjian]], Robert Gonnon, Nathalie Lorson, [[Sophia Grojsman]], and Alienor Massenet.\n\nSince 2014, the fragrance La Vie Est Belle is the best-selling fragrance in Lanc\u00f4me historic market, France.\n\n== Advertising ==\nDespite founder Armand Petijean's assertion that Lanc\u00f4me never advertise, today Lanc\u00f4me is one of the top advertisers in the luxury beauty arena. Its ads can be seen in numerous publications worldwide, from ''Harper's Bazaar'' to French ''Vogue''. Lanc\u00f4me's ads have been shot by the leading photographers, including [[Peter Lindbergh]], [[Mario Testino]], [[Mario Sorrenti]], [[Nick Knight (photographer)|Nick Knight]], [[Steven Meisel]], [[Brigitte Lacombe]], [[Patrick Demarchelier]] and Dusan Reljin.\n\nIn 2012 Lanc\u00f4me premiered a TV advertisement featuring 1930s cartoon icon [[Betty Boop]].<ref>[http://www.fashionablyearly.co.uk/beauty/three-of-the-best-beauty-campaigns-of-2012.html Three of the best beauty campaigns of 2012] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130501003118/http://www.fashionablyearly.co.uk/beauty/three-of-the-best-beauty-campaigns-of-2012.html |date=1 May 2013 }}</ref> Supermodel [[Daria Werbowy]] and Betty talk candidly as Betty gives Daria advice about how to find a role in her \"first big film\". This advertisement has been uploaded to [[YouTube]] by [[Sephora]] and has achieved more than 100000 views in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lancome's Betty Boop Hypnose Star Mascara|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rhtIBTEJfxU|website=YouTube|accessdate=7 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Lanc\u00f4me Paris partnered with the software developer Perfect Corp. to introduce new mobile app experience allowing customers to try on makeup and make direct purchases through the app.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mobilemarketer.com/news/lancome-and-perfect-partner-for-shoppable-app-experiences-focused-on-ar-li/508534/|title=Lanc\u00f4me and Perfect partner for shoppable app experiences focused on AR, live streaming|last=Williams|first=Robert|date=2017-10-31|website=Mobile Marketer|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-16}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Lanc\u00f4me Life Pharmacy Queensgate 2015.JPG|thumb|Counter at [[Green Cross Health|Life Pharmacy]] at [[Westfield Queensgate]] in [[Lower Hutt]], [[Wellington region]], New Zealand]]\n\n=== Spokesmodels and spokespersons ===\nThe brand is represented by actresses, global supermodels, makeup artists and perfumers. Emerging fashion designers have collaborated with the brand, including design duo [[Proenza Schouler]], who created a dress inspired by Lanc\u00f4me's Hypn\u00f4se fragrance, and [[Alber Elbaz]] who designed the packaging for a trio of mascaras.{{citation needed|date=April 2018}}\n\nIn 1978, at the age of eighteen, [[Carol Alt]] became the youngest model to be the face of Lanc\u00f4me. [[Nancy Dutiel]] also modeled for Lanc\u00f4me during this period. More recently, models [[Shalom Harlow]], [[Marie Gillain]] and [[Raica Oliveira]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lukor.com/not-soc/ecos/0601/20140102.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-06-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070926215725/http://www.lukor.com/not-soc/ecos/0601/20140102.htm |archivedate=26 September 2007 }}</ref> have also been spokesmodels for Lanc\u00f4me.\n\nOne of Lanc\u00f4me's longest-running partnerships was with actress [[Isabella Rossellini]]. Signed in 1982, Rossellini was the international face of Lanc\u00f4me for 14 years. In 2016, Rossellini returned for a collaboration with the brand, more than 30 years after she became its first face.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vogue.com/article/isabella-rossellini-lancome-campaign-beauty-63-years|title=Isabella Rossellini Returns to Lanc\u00f4me! How the 63-Year-Old Icon Is Breaking the Beauty Rules|last=Kim|first=Monica|date=2016-03-07|website=Vogue|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-16}}</ref>\n\n[[Ukraine|Ukrainian]]-Canadian model [[Daria Werbowy]] joined the brand in 2005, and has been featured in Lanc\u00f4me ads. Spanish actress and model [[In\u00e9s Sastre]] has represented Lanc\u00f4me as a global spokesmodel since 1996, appearing in dozens of Lanc\u00f4me advertisements over the years.\n\nIn September 2008, Dominican model [[Arlenis Sosa]] became the spokesmodel for the brand.\n\nin 2009, [[Isabella Rossellini]]'s daughter [[Elettra Rossellini Wiedemann]] became the new face of Lanc\u00f4me.\n\nIn 2010, [[Ipsy (company)|ipsy]] founder [[Michelle Phan]] signed a deal with Lanc\u00f4me and became their first Vietnamese spokesperson.\n\nOther renowned actresses have also worked with the brand, including [[Juliette Binoche]], [[Uma Thurman]], [[Drew Barrymore]], [[Mena Suvari]], Laura Morante, [[Kate Winslet]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sassybella.com/index.php/2007/06/12/kate-winslet-is-the-new-face-of-lancome-tresor/|title=Kate Winslet is the new face of Lancome Tresor}}</ref> [[Anne Hathaway]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sassybella.com/index.php/2008/01/03/anne-hathaway-confirmed-as-new-ambassador-for-lancome/|title=Anne Hathaway confirmed as new ambassador for Lancome}}</ref> [[Julia Roberts]], [[Pen\u00e9lope Cruz]], [[Emma Watson]], and currently [[Lily Collins]], [[Lupita Nyong'o]], and [[Zendaya]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.emmawatson.com/en/Latest/Projects/Lancome/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-06-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110315233758/http://www.emmawatson.com/en/Latest/Projects/Lancome/ |archivedate=15 March 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vogue.co.uk/article/actress-lily-collins-new-lancome-ambassador-2014|title=Lily For Lanc\u00f4me|last=Niven|first=Lisa|date=|work=British Vogue|access-date=2018-08-16}}</ref> [[Clive Owen]] was the first male spokesperson for Lanc\u00f4me's Men's skincare range and the fragrance Hypn\u00f4se Homme.\n\n==Digital marketing in Lanc\u00f4me==\n[[Digital marketing]] is used to build relationships with customers and interact with them on time. Lanc\u00f4me targets women in their 40s and younger women have become its new target market.<ref>{{cite web|title=Targeting younger consumers, Lanc\u00f4me's new objective|url=http://ohmyluxury.com/lancome-cosmetics-lupita/|website=Ohmyluxury|accessdate=14 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Social media marketing===\n\nIn 2014, Lanc\u00f4me launched a marketing campaign which combines a loyalty program called 'Lanc\u00f4me Elite Rewards' via [[social media]] platforms. This program gives points as the reward to members for sharing on [[social media]]. Members can earn points by sharing products or connecting with the brand on [[Facebook]], [[Twitter]] and [[Instagram]] and they will get discount while getting enough points.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lanc\u00f4me Gives Points for Social Media in New Loyalty Program|url=https://www.clickz.com/lancome-gives-points-for-social-media-in-new-loyalty-program/31929/|website=Clickz|accessdate=14 March 2018|date=21 April 2014}}</ref> Through the combination of giving rewards and [[social media]] platforms in this campaign, it would attract more engagement and word of mouth publicity that resulted in the increased effectiveness of [[digital marketing]] in Lanc\u00f4me.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Shyu|first1=Maw-Liann|last2=Chiang|first2=Wan-Ju|last3=Chien|first3=Wen-Yuan|last4=Wang|first4=Sheng-Liang|title=Key Success Factors In Digital Marketing In Service Industry and the Development Strategies: A Case Study On Fleur DE Chine At Sun Moon Lake\".|journal=The International Journal of Organizational Innovation|date=1 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Lanc\u00f4me has partnership with [[Airbnb]] and '''Publicis Worldwide's luxury agency 133SH''' to release a new [[social media]] campaign for promoting the new Lanc\u00f4me's UV expert aqua gel.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lanc\u00f4me partners with Airbnb to roll out social campaign|url=http://www.marketing-interactive.com/lancome-partners-with-airbnb-to-roll-out-social-campaign/|website=Marketing-interactive|accessdate=14 March 2018|date=16 June 2017}}</ref> This [[social media]] campaign aimed to reach more young female consumers. They cooperated with three top bloggers, Lanc\u00f4me sent them to [[Airbnb]] homes in three different locations with extreme sun conditions and invited '''133SH''' to film videos for bloggers. The video showcased the effectiveness of the products by the experience of one blogger who explored the effects of the extreme conditions to her skin when applying the products. To spread the message in a further way and interact with the targeted market of 18-25 young Chinese consumers,<ref>{{cite web|title=\u5170\u853b\u643a\u624b\u65f6\u5c1a\u535a\u4e3b\u8054\u7cfb\u4e2d\u56fd\u6d88\u8d39\u8005|url=http://www.marketing-interactive.com/\u5170\u853b\u643a\u624b\u65f6\u5c1a\u535a\u4e3b\u8054\u7cfb\u4e2d\u56fd\u6d88\u8d39\u8005/|website=Marketing-interactive|accessdate=14 March 2018}}</ref> the campaign was released across different [[social media]] and [[e-commerce]] platforms like [[WeChat]].\n\n==Makeup artists==\nLanc\u00f4me has collaborated with several makeup artists. Fred Farrugia created 13 colour collections during his tenure as artistic makeup director (1997\u20132004). His \"Pollen\" collection in 2000 introduced the industry's first lip gloss in a tube: Juicy Tubes.\n\nLanc\u00f4me has several top makeup artists representing it, Aaron De Mey and Sandy Linter. Sandy is Lanc\u00f4me's \"Beauty At Every Age Expert\", and Aaron is Lanc\u00f4me's National Artistic Director for Makeup. Aaron De Mey is no longer the Artistic Director for Lancome. Lanc\u00f4me UK has recently signed Alex Babsky to be the brand's UK Make Up Ambassador.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.diarydirectory.com/daily.aspx|title=DIARY news - DIARY directory|first=X-RM Limited|last=info@x-rm.com}}</ref>\n\nLanc\u00f4me Makeup announced in January 2015 that UK makeup artist Lisa Eldridge has been appointed as its Global Creative Director.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wagoner|first1=Mackenzie|title=Makeup Artist Lisa Eldridge Signs With Lanc\u00f4me|url=http://www.vogue.com/7646253/lancome-creative-director-of-makeup-lisa-eldridge-makeup-artist-youtube-videos/|work=Vogue|accessdate=19 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\n===Hong Kong===\n[[File:Pan Democratic Boycott Loreal in CWB Times Square 20160608.JPG|thumb|200px|Protesters gathered Times Square mall on 8/6 afternoon]]\n[[File:Lancome Kiosk in CWB Lane Crawford after protest 20160608.JPG|thumb|200px|Lancome counters in [[Lane Crawford]] have been post many against message after the protest]]\n{{main|Denise Ho}}\nOn 5 June 2016, Lanc\u00f4me canceled a promotional concert by Hong Kong [[Pro-democracy camp in Hong Kong|pro-democracy]] singer [[Denise Ho]] that was scheduled to be held on 19 June in [[Sheung Wan]].<ref name=\"scraps\">{{cite news|last1=Yeung|first1=Raymond|title=Lancome scraps Hong Kong concert with Denise Ho: online backlash over move to distance itself from pro-democracy star|url=http://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/politics/article/1966367/lancome-scraps-hong-kong-concert-denise-ho-online-backlash|work=South China Morning Post|date=5 June 2016}}</ref> The cancellation was due to a [[boycott]] campaign launched by the [[Communist Party of China|Communist Party]]-controlled ''[[Global Times]]'', which denigrated the [[Cantopop]] star for supposedly advocating Hong Kong and Tibet independence.<ref name=\"scraps\"/> Lanc\u00f4me posted on [[Facebook]] that Ho is not a spokesperson for the brand.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lancome cancels concert after Chinese online backlash|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-36457450|publisher=BBC News|date=6 June 2016}}</ref> The cancellation drew a heavy backlash in Hong Kong, resulting in some Lanc\u00f4me shops in Hong Kong shutting down during the protests.<ref>{{cite news|title=Denise Ho controversy: protesters march despite Lancome closing Hong Kong stores|url=http://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/politics/article/1969055/denise-ho-controversy-protesters-march-despite-lancome|work=South China Morning Post|date=8 June 2016}}</ref> Some Hong Kong merchants refused to accept the political pressure from the [[China|Chinese]] government.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hong Kong merchant cancel corporation with Lanc\u00f4me Chinese|url=http://www.appledaily.com.tw/realtimenews/article/international/20160611/883724/applesearch/%E8%81%B2%E6%8F%B4%E4%BD%95%E9%9F%BB%E8%A9%A9%E3%80%80%E6%B8%AF%E5%95%86%E6%94%BE%E6%A3%84%E8%98%AD%E8%94%BB%E6%AF%8D%E5%85%AC%E5%8F%B8%E8%A8%82%E5%96%AE}}</ref> [[Listerine]], another brand that Ho represents, retained the singer despite criticism from the ''Global Times'' for hiring Ho as its spokesperson.<ref name=\"scraps\"/>\n\nHo ended up playing the concert without Lanc\u00f4me's support.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lin|first1=Gene|title=In Pictures: 3,000 fans and supporters attend Denise Ho concert after controversial Lanc\u00f4me cancellation|url=https://www.hongkongfp.com/2016/06/20/in-pictures-3000-fans-and-supporters-attend-denise-ho-concert-after-controversial-lancome-cancellation/|work=Hong Kong Free Press|date=20 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Portal|Companies}}\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links==\n*[http://www.lancome.com/ Lanc\u00f4me online Boutique ]\n\n{{L'Oreal Brands}}\n{{cosmetics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lancome}}\n[[Category:Cosmetics companies of France]]\n[[Category:Cosmetics brands]]\n[[Category:French brands]]\n[[Category:History of cosmetics]]\n[[Category:L'Or\u00e9al brands]]\n[[Category:Personal care brands]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the French perfumes and cosmetics house|the French commune|Lanc\u00f4me, Loir-et-Cher}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2016}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name\t        = Lanc\u00f4me\n| logo\t        = Lanc\u00f4me logo.svg\n| type\t        = [[Subsidiary]]\n| foundation\t= {{start date and age|1935|df=yes}}\n| founders      = Guillaume d'Ornano<br>Armand Petitjean\n| location_city = Paris\n| location_country = France\n| key_people\t= \n| industry\t= Fashion\n| parent\t= [[L'Or\u00e9al]] (1964\u2013present)\n| products\t= Perfumes and cosmetics\n| revenue\t= \n| net income    = \n| num_employees\t= \n| homepage \t= {{URL|www.lancome.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Lanc\u00f4me''' ({{IPA-fr|l\u0251\u0303kom}}) is a French luxury perfumes and cosmetics house that distributes products internationally.<ref>{{cite news|last=Chesters|first=Anna|title=A brief history of Lanc\u00f4me|url=https://www.theguardian.com/fashion/fashion-blog/2012/mar/19/brief-history-lancome|accessdate=11 March 2013|newspaper=The Guardian|date=19 March 2012}}</ref> Lanc\u00f4me is part of the [[L'Or\u00e9al]] Luxury Products division, which is its parent company and offers [[skin care]], [[fragrances]], and makeup at higher-end prices.\n\n==History==\n[[Image:Lancome NYC Boutique Exterior.jpg|thumb|right|Lanc\u00f4me Boutique on NYC's Upper West Side|Lanc\u00f4me Boutique on NYC's Upper West Side]]\n\nFounded in 1935 by Guillaume d'Ornano and his business partner Armand Petitjean in France, as originally a fragrance house. The name \"Lanc\u00f4me\" was inspired by the forest of Lancosme that lies in the Indre valley in the heart of France in the region of La Brenne - the name was chosen by Guillaume's wife Elisabeth d'Ornano. The roses in the area inspired the company's symbol of the single golden rose.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vogue.in/content/exclusive-80-years-lancome-film/|title=Exclusive: 80 years of Lanc\u00f4me in a 2-minute film}}</ref>\n\nLanc\u00f4me launched its first five fragrances in 1935 at the [[Brussels International Exposition (1935)|World's Fair]] in Brussels: ''Tendre Nuit'', ''Bocages'', ''Conquete'', ''Kypre'' and ''Tropiques''. Petitjean entered into the luxury skincare market, launching Nutrix, his first \"all-purpose repair cream\" in 1936, followed by make-up, cosmetics, and skincare products. Lanc\u00f4me was acquired by L'oreal in 1964, and quickly became part of its luxury products division.\n\n==Products==\n[[File:DFS Galleria Customhouse Lanc\u00f4me 2013.jpg|thumb|Lanc\u00f4me counter at [[DFS Galleria]] Customhouse in [[Auckland]], [[New Zealand]]]]\nThe company provides fragrances, skin care, and makeup. Their most famous products include their mascaras, namely \"Hypn\u00f4se\", their Visionnaire Range which contains a patented ingredient, \"LR 2412\", aimed to improve skin texture color qualities, especially in pore reduction, fine lines and uneven skin tone.\n\nLanc\u00f4me fragrances are made in association with perfumers: Alain Astori, Annick Menardo, Daniela Roche-Andrier, Christian Biecher, [[Jacques Cavallier]], [[Calice Becker]], Pauline Zanoni, [[Maurice Roucel]], [[Thierry Wasser]], [[Christine Nagel]], Armand Petitjean, Gerard Goupy, [[Olivier Cresp]], Harry Fremont, Alberto Morillas, Dominique Ropion, Olivier Polge, [[Francis Kurkdjian]], Robert Gonnon, Nathalie Lorson, [[Sophia Grojsman]], and Alienor Massenet.\n\nSince 2014, the fragrance La Vie Est Belle is the best-selling fragrance in Lanc\u00f4me historic market, France.\n\n== Advertising ==\nDespite founder Armand Petijean's assertion that Lanc\u00f4me never advertise, today Lanc\u00f4me is one of the top advertisers in the luxury beauty arena. Its ads can be seen in numerous publications worldwide, from ''Harper's Bazaar'' to French ''Vogue''. Lanc\u00f4me's ads have been shot by the leading photographers, including [[Peter Lindbergh]], [[Mario Testino]], [[Mario Sorrenti]], [[Nick Knight (photographer)|Nick Knight]], [[Steven Meisel]], [[Brigitte Lacombe]], [[Patrick Demarchelier]] and Dusan Reljin.\n\nIn 2012 Lanc\u00f4me premiered a TV advertisement featuring 1930s cartoon icon [[Betty Boop]].<ref>[http://www.fashionablyearly.co.uk/beauty/three-of-the-best-beauty-campaigns-of-2012.html Three of the best beauty campaigns of 2012] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130501003118/http://www.fashionablyearly.co.uk/beauty/three-of-the-best-beauty-campaigns-of-2012.html |date=1 May 2013 }}</ref> Supermodel [[Daria Werbowy]] and Betty talk candidly as Betty gives Daria advice about how to find a role in her \"first big film\". This advertisement has been uploaded to [[YouTube]] by [[Sephora]] and has achieved more than 100000 views in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lancome's Betty Boop Hypnose Star Mascara|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rhtIBTEJfxU|website=YouTube|accessdate=7 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Lanc\u00f4me Paris partnered with the software developer Perfect Corp. to introduce new mobile app experience allowing customers to try on makeup and make direct purchases through the app.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mobilemarketer.com/news/lancome-and-perfect-partner-for-shoppable-app-experiences-focused-on-ar-li/508534/|title=Lanc\u00f4me and Perfect partner for shoppable app experiences focused on AR, live streaming|last=Williams|first=Robert|date=2017-10-31|website=Mobile Marketer|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-16}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Lanc\u00f4me Life Pharmacy Queensgate 2015.JPG|thumb|Counter at [[Green Cross Health|Life Pharmacy]] at [[Westfield Queensgate]] in [[Lower Hutt]], [[Wellington region]], New Zealand]]\n\n=== Spokesmodels and spokespersons ===\nThe brand is represented by actresses, global supermodels, makeup artists and perfumers. Emerging fashion designers have collaborated with the brand, including design duo [[Proenza Schouler]], who created a dress inspired by Lanc\u00f4me's Hypn\u00f4se fragrance, and [[Alber Elbaz]] who designed the packaging for a trio of mascaras.{{citation needed|date=April 2018}}\n\nIn 1978, at the age of eighteen, [[Carol Alt]] became the youngest model to be the face of Lanc\u00f4me. [[Nancy Dutiel]] also modeled for Lanc\u00f4me during this period. More recently, models [[Shalom Harlow]], [[Marie Gillain]] and [[Raica Oliveira]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lukor.com/not-soc/ecos/0601/20140102.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-06-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070926215725/http://www.lukor.com/not-soc/ecos/0601/20140102.htm |archivedate=26 September 2007 }}</ref> have also been spokesmodels for Lanc\u00f4me.\n\nOne of Lanc\u00f4me's longest-running partnerships was with actress [[Isabella Rossellini]]. Signed in 1982, Rossellini was the international face of Lanc\u00f4me for 14 years. In 2016, Rossellini returned for a collaboration with the brand, more than 30 years after she became its first face.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vogue.com/article/isabella-rossellini-lancome-campaign-beauty-63-years|title=Isabella Rossellini Returns to Lanc\u00f4me! How the 63-Year-Old Icon Is Breaking the Beauty Rules|last=Kim|first=Monica|date=2016-03-07|website=Vogue|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-16}}</ref>\n\n[[Ukraine|Ukrainian]]-Canadian model [[Daria Werbowy]] joined the brand in 2005, and has been featured in Lanc\u00f4me ads. Spanish actress and model [[In\u00e9s Sastre]] has represented Lanc\u00f4me as a global spokesmodel since 1996, appearing in dozens of Lanc\u00f4me advertisements over the years.\n\nIn September 2008, Dominican model [[Arlenis Sosa]] became the spokesmodel for the brand.\n\nin 2009, [[Isabella Rossellini]]'s daughter [[Elettra Rossellini Wiedemann]] became the new face of Lanc\u00f4me.\n\nIn 2010, [[Ipsy (company)|ipsy]] founder [[Michelle Phan]] signed a deal with Lanc\u00f4me and became their first Vietnamese spokesperson.\n\nOther renowned actresses have also worked with the brand, including [[Juliette Binoche]], [[Uma Thurman]], [[Drew Barrymore]], [[Mena Suvari]], Laura Morante, [[Kate Winslet]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sassybella.com/index.php/2007/06/12/kate-winslet-is-the-new-face-of-lancome-tresor/|title=Kate Winslet is the new face of Lancome Tresor}}</ref> [[Anne Hathaway]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sassybella.com/index.php/2008/01/03/anne-hathaway-confirmed-as-new-ambassador-for-lancome/|title=Anne Hathaway confirmed as new ambassador for Lancome}}</ref> [[Julia Roberts]], [[Pen\u00e9lope Cruz]], [[Emma Watson]], and currently [[Lily Collins]], [[Lupita Nyong'o]], and [[Zendaya]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.emmawatson.com/en/Latest/Projects/Lancome/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-06-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110315233758/http://www.emmawatson.com/en/Latest/Projects/Lancome/ |archivedate=15 March 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vogue.co.uk/article/actress-lily-collins-new-lancome-ambassador-2014|title=Lily For Lanc\u00f4me|last=Niven|first=Lisa|date=|work=British Vogue|access-date=2018-08-16}}</ref> [[Clive Owen]] was the first male spokesperson for Lanc\u00f4me's Men's skincare range and the fragrance Hypn\u00f4se Homme.\n\n==Digital marketing in Lanc\u00f4me==\n[[Digital marketing]] is used to build relationships with customers and interact with them on time. Lanc\u00f4me targets women in their 40s and younger women have become its new target market.<ref>{{cite web|title=Targeting younger consumers, Lanc\u00f4me's new objective|url=http://ohmyluxury.com/lancome-cosmetics-lupita/|website=Ohmyluxury|accessdate=14 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Social media marketing===\n\nIn 2014, Lanc\u00f4me launched a marketing campaign which combines a loyalty program called 'Lanc\u00f4me Elite Rewards' via [[social media]] platforms. This program gives points as the reward to members for sharing on [[social media]]. Members can earn points by sharing products or connecting with the brand on [[Facebook]], [[Twitter]] and [[Instagram]] and they will get discount while getting enough points.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lanc\u00f4me Gives Points for Social Media in New Loyalty Program|url=https://www.clickz.com/lancome-gives-points-for-social-media-in-new-loyalty-program/31929/|website=Clickz|accessdate=14 March 2018|date=21 April 2014}}</ref> Through the combination of giving rewards and [[social media]] platforms in this campaign, it would attract more engagement and word of mouth publicity that resulted in the increased effectiveness of [[digital marketing]] in Lanc\u00f4me.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Shyu|first1=Maw-Liann|last2=Chiang|first2=Wan-Ju|last3=Chien|first3=Wen-Yuan|last4=Wang|first4=Sheng-Liang|title=Key Success Factors In Digital Marketing In Service Industry and the Development Strategies: A Case Study On Fleur DE Chine At Sun Moon Lake\".|journal=The International Journal of Organizational Innovation|date=1 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Lanc\u00f4me has partnership with [[Airbnb]] and '''Publicis Worldwide's luxury agency 133SH''' to release a new [[social media]] campaign for promoting the new Lanc\u00f4me's UV expert aqua gel.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lanc\u00f4me partners with Airbnb to roll out social campaign|url=http://www.marketing-interactive.com/lancome-partners-with-airbnb-to-roll-out-social-campaign/|website=Marketing-interactive|accessdate=14 March 2018|date=16 June 2017}}</ref> This [[social media]] campaign aimed to reach more young female consumers. They cooperated with three top bloggers, Lanc\u00f4me sent them to [[Airbnb]] homes in three different locations with extreme sun conditions and invited '''133SH''' to film videos for bloggers. The video showcased the effectiveness of the products by the experience of one blogger who explored the effects of the extreme conditions to her skin when applying the products. To spread the message in a further way and interact with the targeted market of 18-25 young Chinese consumers,<ref>{{cite web|title=\u5170\u853b\u643a\u624b\u65f6\u5c1a\u535a\u4e3b\u8054\u7cfb\u4e2d\u56fd\u6d88\u8d39\u8005|url=http://www.marketing-interactive.com/\u5170\u853b\u643a\u624b\u65f6\u5c1a\u535a\u4e3b\u8054\u7cfb\u4e2d\u56fd\u6d88\u8d39\u8005/|website=Marketing-interactive|accessdate=14 March 2018}}</ref> the campaign was released across different [[social media]] and [[e-commerce]] platforms like [[WeChat]].\n\n==Makeup artists==\nLanc\u00f4me has collaborated with several makeup artists. Fred Farrugia created 13 colour collections during his tenure as artistic makeup director (1997\u20132004). His \"Pollen\" collection in 2000 introduced the industry's first lip gloss in a tube: Juicy Tubes.\n\nLanc\u00f4me has several top makeup artists representing it, Aaron De Mey and Sandy Linter. Sandy is Lanc\u00f4me's \"Beauty At Every Age Expert\", and Aaron is Lanc\u00f4me's National Artistic Director for Makeup. Aaron De Mey is no longer the Artistic Director for Lancome. Lanc\u00f4me UK has recently signed Alex Babsky to be the brand's UK Make Up Ambassador.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.diarydirectory.com/daily.aspx|title=DIARY news - DIARY directory|first=X-RM Limited|last=info@x-rm.com}}</ref>\n\nLanc\u00f4me Makeup announced in January 2015 that UK makeup artist Lisa Eldridge has been appointed as its Global Creative Director.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wagoner|first1=Mackenzie|title=Makeup Artist Lisa Eldridge Signs With Lanc\u00f4me|url=http://www.vogue.com/7646253/lancome-creative-director-of-makeup-lisa-eldridge-makeup-artist-youtube-videos/|work=Vogue|accessdate=19 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\n===Hong Kong===\n[[File:Pan Democratic Boycott Loreal in CWB Times Square 20160608.JPG|thumb|200px|Protesters gathered Times Square mall on 8/6 afternoon]]\n[[File:Lancome Kiosk in CWB Lane Crawford after protest 20160608.JPG|thumb|200px|Lancome counters in [[Lane Crawford]] have been post many against message after the protest]]\n{{main|Denise Ho}}\nOn 5 June 2016, Lanc\u00f4me canceled a promotional concert by Hong Kong [[Pro-democracy camp in Hong Kong|pro-democracy]] singer [[Denise Ho]] that was scheduled to be held on 19 June in [[Sheung Wan]].<ref name=\"scraps\">{{cite news|last1=Yeung|first1=Raymond|title=Lancome scraps Hong Kong concert with Denise Ho: online backlash over move to distance itself from pro-democracy star|url=http://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/politics/article/1966367/lancome-scraps-hong-kong-concert-denise-ho-online-backlash|work=South China Morning Post|date=5 June 2016}}</ref> The cancellation was due to a [[boycott]] campaign launched by the [[Communist Party of China|Communist Party]]-controlled ''[[Global Times]]'', which denigrated the [[Cantopop]] star for supposedly advocating Hong Kong and Tibet independence.<ref name=\"scraps\"/> Lanc\u00f4me posted on [[Facebook]] that Ho is not a spokesperson for the brand.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lancome cancels concert after Chinese online backlash|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-36457450|publisher=BBC News|date=6 June 2016}}</ref> The cancellation drew a heavy backlash in Hong Kong, resulting in some Lanc\u00f4me shops in Hong Kong shutting down during the protests.<ref>{{cite news|title=Denise Ho controversy: protesters march despite Lancome closing Hong Kong stores|url=http://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/politics/article/1969055/denise-ho-controversy-protesters-march-despite-lancome|work=South China Morning Post|date=8 June 2016}}</ref> Some Hong Kong merchants refused to accept the political pressure from the [[China|Chinese]] government.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hong Kong merchant cancel corporation with Lanc\u00f4me Chinese|url=http://www.appledaily.com.tw/realtimenews/article/international/20160611/883724/applesearch/%E8%81%B2%E6%8F%B4%E4%BD%95%E9%9F%BB%E8%A9%A9%E3%80%80%E6%B8%AF%E5%95%86%E6%94%BE%E6%A3%84%E8%98%AD%E8%94%BB%E6%AF%8D%E5%85%AC%E5%8F%B8%E8%A8%82%E5%96%AE}}</ref> [[Listerine]], another brand that Ho represents, retained the singer despite criticism from the ''Global Times'' for hiring Ho as its spokesperson.<ref name=\"scraps\"/>\n\nHo ended up playing the concert without Lanc\u00f4me's support.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lin|first1=Gene|title=In Pictures: 3,000 fans and supporters attend Denise Ho concert after controversial Lanc\u00f4me cancellation|url=https://www.hongkongfp.com/2016/06/20/in-pictures-3000-fans-and-supporters-attend-denise-ho-concert-after-controversial-lancome-cancellation/|work=Hong Kong Free Press|date=20 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Portal|Companies}}\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links==\n*[http://www.lancome.com/ Lanc\u00f4me online Boutique ]\n\n{{L'Oreal Brands}}\n{{cosmetics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lancome}}\n[[Category:Cosmetics companies of France]]\n[[Category:Cosmetics brands]]\n[[Category:French brands]]\n[[Category:History of cosmetics]]\n[[Category:L'Or\u00e9al brands]]\n[[Category:Personal care brands]]\n", "name_user": "Sanderskar